title: For Sale:  LNIB Rare Norinco NHM 91 in original form
postcontent: Purchased in 1995 this rifle has been kepted in its original form with all matching markings/serial numbers on the receiver and bolt.  Comes with everything that came in the original box, as well as the manual, and sales reciept for true authenticity!  Less than 200 rounds thru it this rifle is fully functional with a proven track record and built to last.  Notice little wear on the reciever that all AK's have due to the usage of the saftey lever.This rifle includes:- Original box, manual, and purchase reciept- 1 5 round magazine- 1 10 round magazine- 2 30 round magazines- Has the Bishop buttstock pad- Original bipod- Cleaning rod- Lubricant bottle- Allen wrenchAll laws followed, must have MA LTC, and will transfter using via EFA-10.  Serious buyers only please, no trades.  Any low offers will be ignored, price is firm.BACKGROUND of the Norinco NHM 91:A civilian semi-auto variant of the Russian AKM (Chinese Type 56) rifle, the NHM-91 was built to imitate the appearance of the Russian RPK light machine gun. First imported and marketed in the United States in 1991 by ChinaSports Inc., NHM-91's were modified to meet the requirements of a 1989 Executive Order by President George H. W. Bush prohibiting importation of certain 'assault rifle' configurations of military-style semi-automatic rifles such as the Norinco AKM/AK-47. These modifications included a one-piece U.S.-made thumbhole stock to replace the separate Chinese-made buttstock and pistol grip of the original AKM/RPK rifle and the inclusion of a rivet on the receiver preventing use of standard AK-47, RPK, or AKM magazines. All Chinese rifles were banned under the 1994 Clinton administration or AWB Ban and no Chinese AK variants were allowed to be imported.Based on the Russian RPK light machine gun, the NHM features a stronger receiver and a longer, thicker-profile chrome-lined barrel measuring 20 inches (508mm) compared to the 590 mm (23.2 in) of the original RPK, along with a forward-mounted steel bipod. Like the RPK, the NHM-91 utilizes a heavier-gauge stamped sheet metal receiver built from 1.5mm-thick stamped sheet metal instead of the 1mm thickness typical of a Soviet or European AKM.

title: For Sale:  Japanese Type 2 Paratrooper Rifle
postcontent: For your consideration is this Japanese type 2 Paratrooper Rifle. The primary difference between this rifle and the Type 99 was the fact that it had a bolt that locked the two pieces into place rather than being made of a single piece. The purpose for this was to allow the Japanese paratroopers to carry them in a bag while they jumped and then piece it together on the ground. There were only 17000 of these types of rifles made throughout the duration of the war. Compare this to the millions of K98s, M1 Garands, Nagants, and even T99s and you can understand why it’s a unique bird. The rifle still has a full imperial Chrysanthemum that has not been defaced as well as anti aircraft sites on it. Both halves Match however the bolt is ~50 numbers off from the remainder of the rifle. This is commonly seen on rifles brought back from the Pacific Campaigns as it was common procedures to confiscate the bolt while in transit back to the states. Once back they often just grabbed a random bolt assembly from a large group of readil available ones. This rifle displays well and will be a great addition to any advanced World War 2 firearm collection. I will be bringing it to the WW2 Militaria show this Saturday (Easter Weekend) if you would like to see it. Primary reason for me letting it go is to fund a WW2 era Luger, matching holster and magazines
